{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660055"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22652"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22652"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111140"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15599"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8111"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a painless swelling on the left side of his neck. He has noticed the swelling gradually increasing in size. He denies fever, night sweats, weight loss, or other lumps elsewhere. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks two cans of beer daily. He works as an accountant with no recent travel history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The swelling in his neck is clearly visible (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lipoma","Epidermoid cyst","Branchial cyst","Enlarged lymph node","Thyroid nodule"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a painless neck swelling in the posterior triangle, which has been gradually enlarging over three weeks. The lump is clearly visible. The location posterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and above the supraclavicular fossa, combined with the patient\u0027s significant smoking history, makes metastatic lymphadenopathy the most concerning and likely diagnosis. Lymph nodes in this region commonly receive drainage from the lungs, and lung cancer must be excluded in any smoker presenting with cervical lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnlarged lymph node\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the anatomical location and clinical context. The gradual enlargement over weeks is concerning for malignant infiltration. In a 52-year-old smoker, this requires urgent investigation with imaging (chest X-ray and CT) and likely fine needle aspiration or core biopsy to exclude metastatic disease from lung or head and neck malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a soft, mobile, subcutaneous swelling with well-defined margins. The location posterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle would be unusual for a lipoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents as a well-defined, mobile swelling attached to and arising above the skin with a central punctum. These cysts are typically found in areas with hair follicles and would not present in the deep tissues of the posterior triangle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranchial cyst\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents in younger adults (second to third decade) as a smooth, fluctuant swelling anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle at the junction of its upper and middle thirds. The patient\u0027s age and the posterior location make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid nodule\u003C/strong\u003E would move with swallowing and be located in the midline or paramedian position, anterior to the trachea. The location posterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle excludes thyroid pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Painless lymphadenopathy in a smoker requires urgent investigation to exclude malignancy, particularly lung or head and neck cancers.","Lymph nodes posterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle in the posterior triangle are commonly involved in metastatic disease.","The location, consistency, and clinical context are crucial in differentiating neck lumps."],"references":["Chaturvedi HT, Patel B, Chaturvedi C, et al. Distribution of non\u2011thyroid neck swellings and their clinicopathological correlation. J Family Med Prim Care. 2024; 13:3355-3361. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11368340/","Tan E, Jaya J. An approach to neck masses in adults. Aust J Gen Pract. 2020 May;49(5):267-271. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/may/an-approach-to-neck-masses-in-adults"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22652"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22020"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22020"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bo1fMSjxACW8wCPR7sYHM7MnNO0r1k.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bo1fMSjxACW8wCPR7sYHM7MnNO0r1k.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":462}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T17:26:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T17:27:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15599"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships